Remote Work & Mental Health Project

May Chang & Angely Lee & Danni Zhang

2024-12-11

Summary Objective

The primary goal of this analysis is to evaluate the impact of remote work on employees mental health, work-life balance, and productivity. By leveraging the Remote dataset, we aim to uncover patterns and correlations between remote work factors and key well-being metrics. This analysis will provide actionable insights for organizations to enhance employee support programs and optimize remote work strategies.

Introduction and Objectives

Background

Remote work has become an integral part of modern workplaces, especially in the wake of global shifts in work environments. While offering flexibility and convenience, remote work also presents challenges such as social isolation, mental health struggles, and work-life balance conflicts. Understanding these challenges is essential for creating supportive and sustainable work policies.

Objectives

Evaluate Mental Health Trends:

Investigate the relationship between work-related factors and mental health outcomes. Identify potential stressors associated with remote work.

Assess Work-Life Balance:

Analyze how remote work influences employees work-life balance ratings. Explore correlations between work hours, virtual meetings, and balance ratings.

Examine Productivity Changes:

Study productivity shifts linked to access to mental health resources, physical activity, and satisfaction with remote work.

Generate Insights:

Identify actionable recommendations for organizations to support employees effectively in remote settings.

The Remote dataset consists of 5000 observations and 20 variables, capturing various aspects of employees demographics, work patterns, mental health indicators, and productivity. Below is a detailed description of the variables:

Employee Information: Employee_ID: Unique identifier for each employee (e.g., EMP0001). Age: Employees age (integer). Gender: Gender identity of the employee (Male, Female, Non-binary). Job_Role: The job title of the employee (e.g., HR, Data Scientist, Software Engineer). Industry: Industry sector of employment (e.g., Healthcare, IT, Education, Finance). Work Characteristics: Years_of_Experience: Total years of professional experience (integer). Work_Location: Employees work arrangement (Hybrid, Remote, Onsite). Hours_Worked_Per_Week: Total number of hours worked weekly (integer). Number_of_Virtual_Meetings: Count of virtual meetings attended weekly (integer). Mental Health Indicators: Work_Life_Balance_Rating: Employees rating of their work-life balance on a scale of 1-5 (1 = Poor, 5 = Excellent). Stress_Level: Perceived stress level categorized as Low, Medium, or High. Mental_Health_Condition: Reported mental health condition (e.g., Depression, Anxiety). Support Systems: Access_to_Mental_Health_Resources: Indicates whether the employee has access to mental health resources (Yes, No). Company_Support_for_Remote_Work: Employee rating of company support for remote work on a scale of 1-5. Satisfaction_with_Remote_Work: Employees satisfaction with their remote work arrangement (Satisfied, Unsatisfied). Productivity and Well-being Metrics: Productivity_Change: Changes in productivity reported by the employee (Increase, Decrease, No Change). Social_Isolation_Rating: Employees rating of social isolation on a scale of 1-5 (1 = Not isolated, 5 = Highly isolated). Physical_Activity: Frequency of physical activity (Weekly, Daily, None). Sleep_Quality: Employees self-reported sleep quality (Good, Poor). Additional Information: Region: Geographic region where the employee is located (Europe, Asia, North America).

Variables like Work_Life_Balance_Rating, Stress_Level, and Productivity_Change will provide insights into how remote work influences mental health and performance. Categorical variables such as Work_Location and Access_to_Mental_Health_Resources allow for segmentation and subgroup analysis.

Hybrid_Remote_Data <- Remote %>%
  filter(Remote$Work_Location == "Hybrid" | Remote$Work_Location == "Remote")
# Convert all character columns to factors

  mutate(across(where(is.character), as.factor))

# Recode Stress_Level to be a binary variable where "Low" = 0 ,"Medium and High" = 1

  mutate(b_stress_level = ifelse(Stress_Level == "Low", 0, 1)) %>%
  select(-Stress_Level)

Overall accuracy of the model is approximately 67% which is moderate. Our aim in our further models is to perform better than the null model.

Sensitivity measures the percentage of true positives correctly identified by the model out of all the real positives (TP/TP+FN). This will help identify your true positive rate and indicate if there are high false negatives (predicting low stress levels when its actually medium or high). The fact that sensitivity is 100% is showing that this model is accurate in identifying the true positives (predicting medium or high stress levels when its medium and high stress levels) which is good as you would want to identify the people who are experiencing medium or high stress levels.

Specificity measures the percentage of true negatives correctly identified by the model out of all the real negatives (TN/TN+FP). This will help identify your true negative rate and indicate if there are high false positives (predicting medium or high stress levels when its actually low). With specificity being 0 it is 0% accurate in predicting true negatives (predicting low stress levels when its low).

Key Findings

Right after building the first logistic regression using all the variables, we werent certain how to move forward because the code seemed to have everything right. It surprised us that the outcome was exactly the same as the null model. The second model built had a narrowed down list of predictors as well as a change in the threshold to higher than .5 to see if this could improve specificity. Ultimately, this yielded some different results where specificity increased by 6%, sensitivity decreased slighlty, and accuracy went down to 66% in the train set. Overall, the changes were not significant. Similar observations could be found in the simple decision tree and random forest models.

Iterations of the models: logistic regression, simple decision tree, and random forest were created; however, the results (accuracy, sensitivty, and specificity) were ambiguous. Many models, for example, had their test set perform better than their training set which could imply numerous concerns, such as overfitting of the training set, the training and test set are not diverse enough, etc.

We consistently varied different elements of the models to observe if there were any key differences, such as the threshold for the logistic regression, the different input variables, and comparing results.

We discovered that performing oversampling on the training data helped in attaining more interpretable results. Through oversampling, we found that our best model for predicting b_stress_levels would be logistic regression 3, decision tree 3, or random forest 4. None of these models are not ideal and we can conclude that the Stress_Levels (became b_stress_levels) is not a good predictor for finding out in assessing mental health of employees that work remotely.

Challenges

Although the data has no missing values in any of the variables, the results in our corresponding predictive models for Stress_Levels has not provided any distinguishable outputs.

To mitigate this problem of outputs with the Stress_Levels variable, an attempt to partition the data to 75% and 25% was created to observe if more accurate results would be derived. This partition did not improve results.

Found that oversampling on the training data helped differentiate results from the null model and models were made to observe between non-oversampled vs.oversampled models.

Personal Learning

Not all datasets and choosing an outcome variable will necesarily derive positive results as many models with different input variables were tested, but the ambiguous results remained. This leads us to conclude that the Stress_Levels variable, in which we changed to become a binary variable: b_stress_levels, is not a good target variable to predict mental health trends in terms of stress levels where we wanted to see if working remotely and/or hybrid resulted in lower stress levels.

In class, we learned and utilized the 80% and 20% parition of data; however, it is not the only effective parition and so in this project we tested another partition of 75% and 25% to observe if there were more accurate results. We could further test this with other partitions, such as 70% and 30% or 90% and 10%.

We learned the critical importance of consistently checking and testing our code to ensure both functionality and accuracy. It became clear that just because code executes without errors does not necessarily mean the results are valid or meaningful. For instance, when we compared the performance of our logistic regression model on the train set to the null model, they yielded identical results. This made us carefully review our code and methods. This is because having such an outcome could have indicated potential issues whether it was in our data preparation, feature selection, or model implementation. This experience emphasized the importance of interpreting results thoughtfully and verifying that the model is leveraging predictive features effectively, rather than simply mimicking the baseline.
